Every caucasian person? Let's count how many people are still standing... OK, that was easy. Now, let's start again. Everyone stand up! Every caucasian man in his 30s can sit down... ... That's not really what we can call diversity, is it? ...

Cécilia Bossard <@ceciliaBossard>

What is diversity by the way?

It’s not just about gender or ethnical origins

But also ages, social backgrounds, disabilities, languages, …​

Definition

Let's first take a look at the definition from the Cambridge dictionary. So now that we all know what we are talking about, let's dig deeper into the subject.

What is diversity?

To me, this image really represents diversity We have here different kind of animals, of all colors, size, age, social background, disabilities... Every one has something special and unique to share in this world of friendship. But is it always like that? Are we working in a "Care Bears" world?

Who am I and why am I talking to you today?

Cécilia Bossard, developer

I will first tell you more about me, why I am talking to you today, about diversity. I'm Cécilia Bossard. I have been a developer for more than 10 years. I am currently a free software pixie. I am talking to you as a white woman. So my point of view will not cover everything there is to say about diversity. I will share with you my experience, what I had to face, and still do face today.

Break the stereotypes

As a child, I grew up in a tech-friendly family. My father was a teacher in an elementary school. He was teaching computer sciences to his pupils (it was not so usual in the 80's). Every day, after school, once our homeworks done, we could play with the computers in his classroom. I had the chance to have access to computer early in my life, and without any barrier (we were free to do what we wanted. The possibilities were quite limited anyway ^^) We were never told that computers was not a game for little girls.

Break the stereotypes

As a child, I never heard things like "Girls can't do this" or "Boys can't do that". Later, I realized that I was an exception. I saw the barriers people build in front of children. I saw all the stereotypes against technology and girls. "Technology is not a girls' thing" "Only boy can understand science" I am very glad not to have been confronted to such situation. I wonder if I would have had the same interest in computers ? I'm not so sure...

Break the stereotypes

A good way to break those stereotypes is to smash them as soon as possible. Initiatives like Devoxx4Kids or Coding Goûter are great for that. For instance, in Nantes, We have been organising parent/children coding session for 4 years We have seen little girls become teenagers and still enjoy programming and that's really great ! A girl only came along her little brother who was really interested. During the first session, she only played with her phone but started to look at what the others were doing and finally, she has been coming back month after month, while her little brother never showed up again :-) And I must confess that sometimes, I keep organising those sessions just because of her. We can see that those sessions attract a lot of people and it's a really good thing! But sadly, we often have to force parity so that girls may have time to apply For example, in Nantes, when we are planning a devoxx4kids event, we are providing girls and boys tickets. The content of the event is exactly the same for boys and for girls, but we are saving half of the tickets for girls. Otherwise, all the tickets would we taken by boys. Our next step will be to try to communicate more outside our IT world and give access to this event to children who are not digital natives.

"Hello, Impostor Syndrome!"

(aka "You do not belong here…​")

Despite my tech-friendly environment, I chose to study computer science a bit by accident. When I was in high school, I discovered HTML and Javascript (it was in 2000, when everyone was discovering how to create web pages). I liked the way we could build new things and decided to pursue my studies in computer science. When I arrived at University, I saw that computer science was maybe not so attractive to young women. We were only 10 girls for 90 boys (and I was told it was a really "good" year!). I don't remember my classmates beeing sexist or so, but I clearly remember some of my teachers not talking to girls or making it clear we didn't belong here. Nonetheless, maybe out of sheer stubbornness, I decided to stay. In 2nd year, there were even fewer girls... After these 2 years, I had understood that programming was not a girls' thing. So I decided to pursue my studies to become a project manager! I arrived at my engineering school, where once again, there were only 10% of women... This time I can't remember any discrimination between boys and girls, maybe because I had become used to it. Everything was fine, but there were always a little voice in my head saying "You are just here to enhance the statistics, not because you earned it". Welcome, Impostor Syndrome ! I also have the impression that I was representing the whole womankind. If I was not top of the class, people would be able to say that women are not good computer scientists and would have good reason to exclude us. This stress is added to the global stress upon students shoulders and can be hard to manage.

What can we do to enhance the proportion of women in STEM ?

  • Provide mentorship and role models

  • Give a meaning to the training

  • Connect STEM with other disciplines like humanities or art

If you have the opportinuty to teach things to young people try to provide mentorship and role models. Seeing that people like you have succeeded in this field can be a great support. And being mentored by someone who has faced the same issues can really help get over them. An other way to "attract diversity" into STEM, is to associate disciplines to a meaning For instance, instead of naming your training "Deep dive into Machine learning" you could try "Increase organic farming performance through statistics and algorithm " The content of the training would be the same, but you will not have only math geek students ;-) Be creative and find connections with other disciplines!

Flirting?

Even though everything was going fine at school, I heard people around me say things like "You chose to study computer science only to find a good husband". (By the way, do you ask nurse or a teacher if they chose this job to find a wife?) It was also the time when I started playing video games. I found it great to be able to play online with other people. But, if you are a woman playing video games online, you're always accused of flirting. You are playing just to find a boyfriend, not because girls just want to have fun ;) ... And honestly, it's not only my lack of time that has made me stop playing online video games... I'm just fed up with having to justify myself all the time for something I do (I did) because I enjoyed it. On the other side, maybe have you experienced sponsoring at school ? In my case, either at University or Engineer school, we were assigned to sponsors. It was the student union that took care of this matching. And strangely, all girls were "attributed" to the members of the student union It is hard to think that this matching was made without afterthoughts... And in this condition, how can you expect your sponsor to be caring and dare ask for help ? Despite these litte issues, everything was going well :-)

Hello again, Impostor Syndrome !

After graduating, I started to work in a big IT company. I was told that because I was junior, I had to start as a developer, and could become project manager after a few years. Great! Let's do this! So I programmed, learned new frameworks, new languages, had fun learning new things... (and enjoyed it) But every time I was presented to clients, I was told to wear a dress or a skirt. Did the client only choose me because of my legs or was it because I had the required technical competences ? Was it only to "feminize" the work place ? People told me it was an asset to be a woman, but I saw this as a burden. I was just seen as THE woman of the team, like a green plant or a trophee you set in the middle of the office for everyone to see. Hello again, dear impostor syndrome !

What can we do ?

  • Take care of your job description!

    • Free pizza / bier / table tennis, …​

    • vs. Remote work, time to take care of your beloved ones, equity in treatment, respect, …​

Be really careful about your job description What kind of person do you want to attract ? Is it young people who want to have fun and can stay late ? In this case, the first description can be fine Or do you want more mature people with a good life balance, involved in communities, ... ? In that case, reflect it in your job description and show what you can offer

What can we do ?

Change your recruitment process ?

  • Anonymous resume

  • Technical recruitment tests

  • …​

When you receive resumes, anonymise them Even though we do not want to, we have implicit biases (about gender, social background, age, ...) that can blur our opinion Having no name, photograph, age, address, on a resume can help reduce those bias And candidates know that if they are chosen, it is thanks to their competences. If you are searching for some technical skills, you can also provide technical tests With those tests, you will not be influenced by which school people attended, which company they worked for, which projects they worked in, ... to have an idea about their technical level.

Bad luck ?

Loss of meaning

After a few years, I started to see my classmates becoming project manager, architect, technical referent... So I thought that it was the moment for my career to evolve too! But I was told that I didn't have enough technical background or experience for now. But why did all my classmates, who were by the way all white men, have the opportunity to evolve and not me? Was it just bad luck, a lack of opportunities? Or am I so bad at what I do? I wasn't even given a chance to try... And so, I started to lose interest in my work

"It was just a joke ;-)"

meet grumpy me

Because I was not feeling so well at work, I started to become a little grumpy Despite all the jokes my collegues used to tell! In every team I worked with, there were (are) always sexist jokes Once or twice, it can be OK, sometimes even fun, but not all day long... And when I got upset, people just told me "It was just a joke", "you're really annoying with your angry feminism". So I became even grumpier...

Well-being

Learn to know the person you are working with

Well-being is not just about sexists jokes. There are many situations at work that can deteriorate team work For instance, why can't persons who are singles take days off during school holidays ? Are they not allowed to spend time with their families ? Speaking of holiday, realize that christian holidays is not the norm for everyone. Please considerate that in your schedules. If people are muslims in your team try to avoid a big launch of your project during Ramadan They might not be really effective and people might blame them because of their religion Whereas nobody is deploying a new version of a software for Christmas... Be also careful on the tasks distribution I have too often seen things like "Front-end for girls" / "Back-end for boys" Because, apparently, women know how to make pretty things Are you really sure about it? For instance, have you already seen me draw? (hint: it's really not pretty) Just ask people what they prefer to work on (be agile? :-D) Another thing you should be aware of, is meeting times Some people have to take care of loved ones / significant others and can't stay late, some have buses to catch, some can't work efficiently in the morning... You are working with human beings, try to adapt! Just ask what the best time would be and timebox the meetings You will see people more relaxed and able to concentrate on the discussions Last but not least, let's talk about clothes I've noticed that every summer, the problem reappears Why can't we see men's legs at work while women can wear short skirts ? Would it be the same if women didn't shave their legs ? I have never been given a real answer to this question... Nonetheless, equality goes both ways.

Well-being

  • Kindness, moral support

  • Mind your words

  • Sponsorship

Show that you care and accept everyone. Do not accept aggressive behavior towards minorities Do not let even little misbehavior become normal Mind your words Words are easilly said and can't be erased We can't read over what we are saying (but we can thing about it before !)

Well-being

  • Communication

    • Speaking

    • Listening

Little actions can also be implemented in our day to day life Typically while we communicate Be careful about the way you speak. Not everyone has the same knowledge. When citing someone, just take time to make sure everyone knows the reference or explain it. When talking about a framework, make sure everyone knows it or again, take time to explain. It's during such conversations that people can feel that they are set aside and do not belong. And it is the same with humor. Not everyone has the same sense of humor and some jokes might be offensive to certain people. Don't be afraid to say "I'm sorry" if you hurt someone. Speaking of hurting someone, try to mind your swear words If you are like me when you are coding, swear words are easilly said. Try not to use sexualized swear words like in french "Putain" (I know, it is not easy!) or talk about a really "sexy" framework Some expression can be offensive towards people even when it is not meant to be. And a little thing that happens really often, is using the word "guys" to mean "people". It's actually not a gender neutral word... It might be felt like a daily reminder that women can not be part of the team. While speaking is important, listening is even more important! Try to listen to people and let them speak, particuly in meetings. Make sure every one had the same opportunity to express their opinion, whatever their gender, age, experience, ...

Motherhood

developers = children?

When I had my first child, after my maternity leave, my manager told me that everything would be different, now that I was a mom. I could start managing people and projects. What?!?! Just because I could barely manage my 3 months old daughter, it meant I could manage a bunch of developers and clients? What I really saw was that I was not treated like my male colleagues concerning parenthood. When my daughters are sick, I am the one who is called for by school, even though their father is working at home. I'm always reminded that women are supposed to take care of their children and are supposed to stay at home or work part-time... I thought we were in 2018, not in 1818?

Day to day life

  • Chores distribution (at home and at work)

Cooking, cleaning, child care, ... Men also do all these things. So just give them time to take care of their children, to be at home if they want to. Allowing remote work can also be a great solution ! And women are not the only ones who want to work part-time. It's the day to day concerns that will drive peolpe away, no matter how much energy a company puts into big-picture efforts.

Investment into communities

After the birth of our second daughter, my husband and I decided to give my career a boost while he put his aside (and I thank him hugely for it!) So I became more active into communities and started to really see what was going on. Every time I was at a meetup or at a conference, people started to ask me if I understood what was said, if I was here to recruit people or to meet some clients. I can say this really, really bothered me... So, maybe the only way to show people you are competent is to give technical talks at conferences ? But what should I talk about? I'm not "technical enough"! At that time, I joined the Duchess France community and tried to help enhance the proportion of women in computer science. We also started a group in Nantes called Women In Tech (But because we all lack time, it is not really active...) And thanks to them, I started to dare speak at conferences! But I still do not dare speak about technical subjects, only about soft skills...(But I'm working on it!) I'm also glad I had the opportunities to meet other women in tech who faced the same issues I did Communities are really important and can provide a great support.

Why is diversity even important?

OK. You might be thinking "Yeah, it's not cool, but why is it even important?" Why do we need diversity among our teams?

Why is diversity even important ?

A diverse group of problem-solvers usually has a better chance of outperforming a less diverse team, thanks to the broader range of experiences each member brings to the table.

Diversity among a group of problem solvers is more important than individual excellence. People from different backgrounds do, on average, tend to approach work and problem solving differently. And solving problem is exactly what we do every day! These differences can bring new perspectives needed to promote innovation.

Do not fear to talk about it

#meToo

I you feel discriminated or witness such behaviour do not hesitate to talk about it. The more we will talk about these issues, the likelier things are to change. If we all act as if it didn't exist, nothing will ever be done against discrimination.

And if anything goes wrong…​

  • "Defenseur des droits"

  • Laws again discrimination

I hope you won't have to use it, but if anything goes wrong, we have laws against discrimination. In France, we also have a legislation called the "Defenseur des droits". 
(ex: https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000018877783[LOI n° 2008-496 du 27 mai 2008])

The goal is not to have a perfectly diverse team but a team with enough diversity

Diversity attracts diversity

The problem becomes exponentially easier to solve once you’ve begun to solve it ^^
